# PML app screens (canonical pattern)

## Mandatory written specs (always read when in scope)

This rule has **`alwaysApply: true`**. Together with the repo paths below, treat them as **on for every message** when the work matches their scope. The user should **never** have to paste or name these files for routine UI / screen / flow work.

| Spec | Path | Read when |
|------|------|-----------|
| Theme, Figma mapping, flows | **`DESIGN.md`** (repo root) | Any UI that could touch documented theme, typography, Figma, or flows |
| Registry, generation, flows, payments | **`design-system-schema/screen-generation-rules.md`** | Screens, widgets, multi-step flows, registry-aligned codegen, or “use only registry building blocks” work |
| Phone shell, scroll, section rhythm | **`design-system-schema/layout-candidates.md`** | Choosing or implementing the **376px** frame, **`.sh-content`** scroll model, **Stock Home**–style sections, or a new page shell |
| PRD / Figma / images / PDF / wireframe → DS mapping | **`.cursor/rules/pml-reference-inputs.mdc`** | User attaches or links **PRD**, **Figma**, **PNG** (or other image), **PDF**, **wireframe**, or design reference URLs for screen or flow work |
| Screen / component checklist (this file) | **`.cursor/rules/pml-screen-patterns.mdc`** | Any request in the enforcement paragraph below |

**Workspace:** **`StoryBook PML`** — prefer **`src/components/`** patterns and Storybook compositions over ad hoc shells; there is **no** bundled **`src/PML App/`** product folder.

Where **`DESIGN.md`**, the **schema** docs, and **this rule** overlap, **follow all**; if they conflict, follow the **user’s explicit instruction**, then update the doc or rule that should become standard.

## Automatic enforcement — the user does not need to remind you

For **any** request to **make**, **create**, **build**, **add**, **implement**, **design**, or **refactor** UI, screens, widgets, or flows (including “quick” or vague prompts), you **must** follow **this rule** and the **mandatory written specs** table above **automatically**.

- **Read `DESIGN.md` (repo root) when it exists** and the work could touch documented theme, typography, Figma mapping, or flows—**even if the user does not mention the file.**
- **Read `design-system-schema/screen-generation-rules.md`** when implementing or planning **screens, widgets, flows, or registry-driven UI**—**even if the user does not mention the file.**
- **Read `design-system-schema/layout-candidates.md`** when implementing or choosing **page shell / scroll / section layout** for PML app screens—**even if the user does not mention the file.**
- **Only bypass** these conventions when the user **explicitly** opts out in writing (e.g. prototype-only, external stack).

When adding or refactoring **in-app screens**, **multi-step flows**, or **new UI** (e.g. feature folders under `src/`, Storybook stories), you **must** follow the pipeline below. Do **not** ship screens built only from ad hoc utility CSS (e.g. raw Tailwind palette names) and one-off markup while ignoring the design system—unless the user **explicitly** opts out in writing.

**Default agent behavior:** For any brief (PRD excerpt, Figma link, screenshot, or chat instruction), **analyze the requirement first**, then **map it to existing components and tokens**, then **implement**. The deliverable is **our** layout language (this repo’s components + CSS variables), not a generic HTML/CSS sketch.

## Requirement analysis → design-system build (PRD, Figma, references)

Use this when translating **PRD**, **Figma**, **screen references**, or **product specs** into code:

1. **Extract** — Scope, flows, states (loading / empty / error), copy, **INR** formatting, density (phone **376px** column). Note interactive patterns (tabs, filters, lists, carousels).
2. **Map before coding** — List which **`src/components/`** primitives apply (discover usage via **`*.stories.tsx`** in the same folder as the component). Assign **spacing, color, type, radii** to **`src/tokens/`** semantic variables. Choose a **screen shell** reference (**`StockHomePage`** + **`StockHome.css`**, or an existing PML app page such as **`Discover`** when the feature matches).
3. **Figma** — If the user provides a link, use **file key** and **node id** when using design tools. Prefer **hierarchy, spacing rhythm, and component intent**; in code, bind to **semantic tokens**, not one-off hex from the file unless no token exists (then add or extend tokens deliberately).
4. **Storybook** — Treat Storybook as the **catalog of truth** for how components behave and compose. Prefer **extending** a component or adding a **story** over cloning markup. New composites (widgets, screen sections) should get a **story** when they are reusable or review-critical—unless the user opts out.
5. **Do not** — Add parallel “local” button/card/chip styles that duplicate **`src/components/`** for the same role. Do not invent a second spacing or color system beside **`src/tokens/`** for app UI.
6. **Document** — After shipping a Figma-linked or PRD-owned flow, **update `DESIGN.md`** so the repo keeps one written spec for theme, tokens, and mapping.

If inputs are ambiguous, **infer conservatively** (tokens + existing patterns) and **call out assumptions** in the PR or reply—not unscoped custom CSS.

## Mandatory pipeline (create screen / design / flow)

1. **`DESIGN.md` (repo root)** — **Read it when present** before implementing UI that could relate to documented flows, theme, or Figma. Do **not** wait for the user to name this file. It records **theme, typography roles, spacing intent, and token ↔ Figma mapping**. Align new work with those semantics; **update `DESIGN.md`** when you add or change a documented Figma-linked flow so the single doc stays the written spec.
2. **`design-system-schema/screen-generation-rules.md`** — **Read it** before implementing or planning **screens, widgets, multi-step flows, or registry-aligned UI**. It governs **`design-system-schema/design-system.registry.json`**, missing-piece placeholders, layout/styling discipline, and flow/payment accuracy. Do **not** wait for the user to name this file.
3. **`design-system-schema/layout-candidates.md`** — **Read it** before choosing **page shell** (phone column, **`.sh-content`**, bottom nav sibling, **Stock Home** reference). Do **not** wait for the user to name this file.
4. **Storybook** — Treat Storybook as the **component catalog** for this repo: discover and reuse **`src/components/`** primitives (e.g. `Header`, `Card`, `Chip`, `Button`, `SectionHeader`, `ListItem`, `Icon`, `BottomNav`). Prefer **extending** an existing component over duplicating patterns. When the user asks for a **new screen** and a preview is appropriate, **wire it in the app shell** and/or add or update a **story** so the screen stays discoverable—unless the user says not to add Storybook (e.g. auth-only flows).
5. **Tokens** — Use **`src/tokens/`** (`colors.css`, `numbers.css`, `typography.css`, etc.) and semantic CSS variables (`--surface-*`, `--text-*`, `--spacing-*`, `--card-padding-*`, …). **No raw hex or arbitrary pixel soup for app chrome** when a token exists. **`index.css`** already loads tokens for the app; screen CSS should **not** redefine a parallel palette.
6. **Screen pattern (this doc)** — Match **`StockHomePage`** + **`StockHome.css`** for frame, scroll, sections, and rhythm; use the **Checklist** and **Components** sections below for every new screen.

If any step conflicts with a **direct user instruction**, follow the user and then **update this rule or `DESIGN.md`** when the new approach should become standard.

---

When adding or refactoring **in-app screens** (e.g. in a feature folder or Storybook full-page stories), treat the **phone column + `.sh-content` scroll** pattern in **`layout-candidates.md`** / **`docs/LEARNINGS.md`** as the reference (historical **`StockHomePage` + `StockHome.css`**). Match its **structure, spacing, tokens, and component choices** unless the user explicitly asks for something different.

## Frame and shell

- **Phone column:** `376px` wide (e.g. `.stock-home`), `100vh`, `display: flex; flex-direction: column`, `background: var(--surface-level-4)`, `overflow: hidden`, `text-align: left` (reset root centering).
- **Scroll:** Main body scrolls inside **`.sh-content`** (`flex: 1`, `overflow-y: auto`, `overflow-x: hidden`, bottom padding e.g. `--spacing-16`).
- **Preview host:** This repo has **no** `AppShell` — center phone-width frames in **Storybook** (or your own wrapper); do not assume a global dev aside/nav harness.

## Tokens (no one-off magic numbers)

- **Spacing:** `--spacing-*` from `src/tokens/numbers.css` (e.g. section gaps `--spacing-56`, common gutters `--spacing-16`, `--spacing-32`).
- **Cards:** default padding is **`--card-padding-block`** (24px) × **`--card-padding-inline`** (16px) — use `Card` and/or these variables; do not invent new card insets per screen. **Cards do not use an outer border by default** — depth reads from **surface fill + radius** only. That applies to **(1)** plain `<Card>` (**no `stroke` prop**) and **(2)** screen-level card-like surfaces built in page CSS (e.g. shortcut rows, carousel tiles, `button` cards): use **`border: none`** (or equivalent) and **do not** add a default **`1px` hairline box** around the card edge unless **PRD, Figma, or explicit user instruction** calls for an outlined / stroked card.
- **Card-like stacked list surfaces** (single elevated **`--surface-level-1`** stack with multiple rows — implemented with **`Card`** *or* the same visual in feature CSS, e.g. loyalty task lists, savings transaction lists): Treat them like **`Card`** for shape and rhythm; **PRD, Figma, or explicit user instruction** can override any item below.
  - **Corner radius:** **`border-radius: var(--radius-24)`** — same token as **`Card`**. Do **not** default these stacks to **`--radius-16`** (or other radii) unless the spec documents a different corner treatment.
  - **Row dividers (two approved models — choose per surface; document in screen CSS):**
    - **Custom row stacks** (list region uses **`padding: 0`** on the elevated **`Card`** / shell, or **block-wrapped** flex rows): hairlines **between** rows must **not** span the full inner width of the **unpadded** card; inset **`var(--card-padding-inline)`** from **each** side (e.g. **`margin-left` / `margin-right: var(--card-padding-inline)`** on the divider or a following-row **`::before`**). Rows that are **`display: flex`** need a **block wrapper** per row so the divider is not a flex item — pattern and examples in **`docs/LEARNINGS.md`** (removed loyalty / goals demos used **`__task-wrap`**, **`__tx-row-wrap`** + **`::before`**).
    - **`Card` + stacked `ListItem` rows** (default **`Card`** keeps **`padding-inline: var(--card-padding-inline)`** around the list): treat **`Card`** horizontal padding as the **lateral inset from the rounded outer edge** (same **16px** token as section gutters). **`ListItem`** hairlines default **edge-to-edge** on the row (**`separatorInset`** is **`false`** by default). If a row opts into **`separatorInset`** (hairline after the avatar), scope **`*.css`** on the **`Card`** so **`.li-item__separator--inset`** can be forced to **`left: 0; right: 0`** when the spec wants full width inside the padded card. Use **`showSeparator`** on each **`ListItem`** except the last. **Reference:** **`docs/LEARNINGS.md`** (Card + ListItem divider model). **`ListItem`** separators must use a **registered** border token in **`ListItem.css`** (**`--border-neutral-weak`** — not undefined vars).
  - **First / last row padding (inside the stack):** The **first** row’s content should use **`padding-top: var(--card-padding-block)`** (**24px**); the **last** row should use **`padding-bottom: var(--card-padding-block)`**. **Middle** rows use denser vertical padding on the row (e.g. **`--spacing-12`**) so rhythm between dividers stays tight — use **`:first-child` / `:last-child`** on the **row wrapper** scoped to the list (see **`docs/LEARNINGS.md`**). A **single** row is both first and last (**24px** top and bottom). **Horizontal** padding on each row remains **`var(--card-padding-inline)`** (or equivalent) so copy and controls align with **`Card`** body insets — same idea as **`ListItem`** inside **`Card`**, whether you use **`ListItem`** or custom row markup.
  - **Section content (`SectionHeader` + stack):** Do **not** stack **24px** twice: if the **list** already applies **first/last row** **`--card-padding-block`**, keep the section content wrapper at **`padding-top` / `padding-bottom: 0`** (horizontal gutter unchanged). If the list is flush to the wrapper with **no** inner first/last row pad, you may use **`padding-top` / `padding-bottom: var(--card-padding-block)`** on the **section** wrapper instead — **PRD, Figma, or explicit user instruction** chooses the variant; default to **one** layer only.
- **`TextField` inside `Card`:** The design-system **`TextField`** root is **`width: 344px`** in `TextField.css` (full phone content width). **`Card`** is **`max-width: 344px`** *including* horizontal padding, so the **inner** content box is **narrower** than 344px. Unscoped `TextField`s therefore **overflow** the card visually (inputs align to 344px while the card body is ~312px). **Always** scope overrides on auth / form screens, e.g. `.my-page__form .textfield { width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-width: 0; }`, with **`form` / column wrapper** using **`width: 100%; min-width: 0`** where the parent is a flex item. Set **`Card`** to **`width: 100%; max-width: var(--card-width); box-sizing: border-box`** when it sits in a centered column. See **`LoginPage.css`** (`login-page__form`, `login-page__card`).
- **Stacked `TextField` spacing (auth / card forms):** For a column **`form`** (or equivalent flex column) of full-width **`TextField`**s, use **`gap: var(--spacing-24)`** between rows — **24px** via token, not **`--spacing-16`**, unless **PRD, Figma, or explicit user instruction** calls for a denser form. Do not add extra **`margin-top`** on the primary CTA wrapper when **`gap`** already separates the last input from that block (avoids double spacing). Reference **`SignUpPage.css`** (`sign-up-page__form`) and **`LoginPage.css`** (`login-page__form`).
- **Colors/type:** semantic tokens (`--surface-*`, `--text-*`, `--border-*`, `--font-weight-*`, etc.) from existing CSS variables — not raw hex for UI chrome.
- **Icons (glyph colour):** For **`Icon`** usage and icon slots in screen or widget CSS, default the glyph to **`color: var(--icon-neutral-strong)`** unless **PRD, Figma, or explicit user instruction** assigns another semantic role (**`--icon-primary-strong`**, **`--icon-positive-strong`**, **`--icon-negative-strong`**, **`--icon-neutral-moderate`**, **`--icon-neutral-medium`**, etc.). Do not use raw hex for icon fill; match patterns in **`Tile.css`**, **`BottomNav.css`**, **`Alert.css`**, and **`Dropdown.css`**.

## Currency (INR)

- **No space** between the **₹** symbol and the amount: write `₹8,00,694`, `+₹240.50`, not `₹ 8,00,694` or `+ ₹240.50`. Apply in copy, props, and Storybook defaults.

## Section pattern

- **Vertical rhythm:** blocks use **`.sh-section`** with **`margin-top: var(--spacing-56)`** (adjust only if design explicitly differs).
- **Typical block:** `SectionHeader` (**`size="extra-large"`** — primary section title row) + content. **Treat this as mandatory for new work:** default every new **`SectionHeader`** to **`extra-large`** unless a documented exception applies (see **`SectionHeader`** subsection below).
- **Content wrapper:** wrap cards / primary content in **`.sh-section__content`** with **`padding: var(--spacing-16)`** (full padding around the block). Keep the same **16px horizontal alignment** as section titles (`SectionHeader` uses `padding: 0 var(--spacing-16)` on `.sh`).
- **Exception:** when a widget manages its own horizontal inset (e.g. `ReminderWidget` `.rw__cards`), follow that component’s CSS — do not double-wrap with extra horizontal padding unless intentional.

### `SectionHeader` — size, chevron, not trailing “See more”

- **Default size (mandatory for new screens):** Always use **`size="extra-large"`** on **`SectionHeader`** for new PML app section titles — in code, Storybook, and PRs — unless **(1)** **PRD, Figma, or explicit user instruction** specifies a smaller size for **documented density**, or **(2)** the **static-heading exception** below applies. **`extra-large`** is the standard product title band; **do not** choose **`large`**, **`medium`**, or **`small`** by habit or to avoid the chevron. Legacy pages (e.g. some **`StockHomePage`** rows) may still show **`large`** + **`showChevron`** until refactored; **new** sections default **`extra-large`**.
- **References that show text links (“View all”, “View more”, “See all”, “See more”, …):** Treat that intent as **chevron drill-in**, not a **`SectionHeader`** text link. Implement **`SectionHeader`** with **`size="extra-large"`** (chevron is always shown for **`extra-large`**) and **`trailing="none"`** — same as list sections on **`StockHomePage`**. Do **not** use **`trailing="link"`** or **`trailing="text"`** to recreate **“View all”** / **“View more”** beside the title; the chevron carries the affordance.
- **Default (PML app list / summary sections):** Use **`SectionHeader`** with **`showChevron`** and **`trailing="none"`** — same rhythm as **`StockHomePage`** (`Your stocks`, `Goals`, `Pickup where you left`, …). The chevron signals **drill-in / full list**; do **not** place **“See more”**, **“View all”**, **“+ Add”**, or similar beside the title via **`trailing="link"`** or **`trailing="text"`** for that pattern.
- **When navigation ships later:** Keep **`showChevron`**; make the header row (or screen) handle tap — do not revert to a text link beside the title unless **PRD / Figma / explicit user instruction** requires that copy.
- **Other `trailing` values (`button`, `icons`, …):** Use only when the spec calls for a **distinct control** (e.g. icon action, compact CTA) — not as a substitute for the standard list-header affordance above.
- **Static-heading exception (only when chevron must not appear):** **`SectionHeader`** at **`extra-large`** always renders a chevron today. For titles that **never** navigate, expand, or imply a full list, do **not** ship a misleading chevron: use **`size="large"`** + **`showChevron={false}`** + **`trailing="none"`**, and note the exception in the PR or beside the instance. Prefer **`MISSING_COMPONENT`** / a **`SectionHeader`** enhancement if the product needs **XL typography without a chevron** — do **not** silently default to **`large`** elsewhere.

## Components (reuse, don’t reinvent)

- **Header / tabs / chips in header:** `Header` from design system.
- **`Icon`:** Prefer **`Icon`** from **`src/components/`**; scope colour on a wrapper class (default **`--icon-neutral-strong`** per **Tokens → Icons**).
- **Section titles:** `SectionHeader` — default **`size="extra-large"`**; chevron + **`trailing="none"`** for list-style sections (see **`SectionHeader` — size, chevron** above).
- **Surfaces:** `Card` for card UI — **default is no outer border** (`stroke` off); use `stroke` only when the design specifies an outlined card. The same **no outer border by default** rule applies to **custom card-shaped blocks** in feature CSS (`*Page.css`, page-scoped `*.css`, etc.): prefer **`background` + `border-radius`** without a wrapping border token unless the spec requires outline. **Multi-row stacks** that read as one card (lists of rows inside a rounded surface) follow **Tokens → Card-like stacked list surfaces** (`--radius-24`, **row dividers** per the **two models** there — **wrapper + `::before`** vs **`Card` + `ListItem`**, **first/last row** **`--card-padding-block`**, optional section wrapper vertical pad — **not** both). **Chip** default for dense filters/time ranges (e.g. portfolio time row) is often **`extra-small`** (see `Chip.css` / Stock Home); **PRD, Figma, or explicit user instruction** may specify **`small` / `medium` / `large`** for filter strips—follow that over this default when documented.
- **Rows:** **`ListItem`** for standard list rows inside **`Card`** or lists that map to the registry. **Custom** stacked rows in a **card-like list surface** (feature CSS) must still honor **Tokens → Card-like stacked list surfaces** for **horizontal** inset (**`--card-padding-inline`**), **first/last** **`--card-padding-block`**, and **row dividers** per the **two models** there (**wrapper + `::before`** vs **`Card` + `ListItem`** with scoped separator overrides) — do not invent a parallel list row system.
- **Bottom bar:** `BottomNav` + `HomeIndicator` — default solid **`--surface-level-1`** (no frosted/blur unless specified).
- **Reminders:** `ReminderWidget` — **carousel** horizontal inset uses **flex `::before` / `::after` spacers** + `scroll-padding-inline` (not padding-only on `overflow-x: auto`). Do not “fix” carousel edge stickiness by removing that pattern.

## Stock Home–specific rules (portfolio area)

Use **`PortfolioWidget`** (`.pw__chips`, `.pw__values`) on Stock Home; do not duplicate this block in page CSS.

- **Time-range chips row (`.pw__chips`):** `Chip` **`extra-small`**, row **`justify-content: space-between`**, horizontal inset **`padding-inline: var(--card-padding-inline)`**, **no** horizontal scroll unless product requires it.
- **Gap below chips to key values (`.pw__values`):** **`margin-top: var(--spacing-32)`** between chips and the Invested / Returns block.
- **Horizontal strips** (e.g. **`Ticker`** / `.tk`): `padding: 0 var(--spacing-16)` (or `--card-padding-inline`), optional `overflow-x: auto` + hidden scrollbar where a scrolling strip is intended.

## File placement

- New screen components: a **feature folder** under `src/` (not `src/components/`), styles alongside **`*Page.css`** or **`StockHome.css`**-style prefixed classes (`sh-*` or a consistent new prefix per screen).
- Shared UI: **`src/components/`** — extend existing components and tokens before adding parallel implementations.

## Shared components — platform density (guardrails)

For **CSS under `src/components/`** (not product screens): prefer **token variables** over new magic **`px`** so Mobile / Tablet / Web scaling stays consistent; do not embed **platform branching** in components. **Legitimate exceptions** include hairlines, device-chrome mocks, logos/illustrations, and values with no token yet (then extend tokens deliberately). Human + doc guardrails: **`CONTRIBUTING.md`**, **`src/components/README.md`**, Storybook **Introduction → Contributor checklist**. ESLint does not lint `.css`.

## Checklist before shipping a new screen

1. **Requirement mapped:** PRD/Figma/brief translated to **component list + tokens** (not ad hoc layout first).
2. **Written specs:** **`DESIGN.md`** consulted and updated if this flow is (or should be) documented against Figma; **`design-system-schema/screen-generation-rules.md`** followed for registry / missing-piece / flow rules; **`design-system-schema/layout-candidates.md`** applied for shell and scroll structure (do **not** rely on the user attaching these).
3. **Components + Storybook:** screen composes **`src/components/`**; story and/or **App shell** entry added when previews are in scope (skip only if the user said so).
4. **Tokens only** for layout chrome: spacing, color, type, radii from **`src/tokens/`** — no parallel ad hoc theme.
5. Width **376px** column + **`.sh-content`** scroll pattern (or documented exception for the feature).
6. **Sections** use **`--spacing-56`** (or documented exception) + **`SectionHeader`** (**`size="extra-large"`** by default) + **`sh-section__content`** where appropriate; list-style section titles use **`showChevron`** + **`trailing="none"`** (not **`trailing="link"`** for “See more” / “View all” / “View more” / “+ Add”). If the **reference** shows **“View all”** / **“View more”** beside a list header, map it to the **chevron** pattern — do not ship a text link unless **PRD/Figma / explicit user instruction** requires that copy.
7. **16px** horizontal rhythm via **tokens** (`--card-padding-inline` / `--spacing-16`).
8. **Cards** use **`Card`** + **`--card-padding-*`**, **without** `stroke` unless the design requires a border; **card-like stacked lists** follow **Tokens → Card-like stacked list surfaces** (**`--radius-24`**, **row dividers** per the **two models** there — **wrapper + `::before`** vs **`Card` + `ListItem`**, **first/last row** **`--card-padding-block`**, section vertical pad **only** if not already applied on rows — no double **24px**) unless **PRD/Figma / explicit user instruction** differs.
9. **`TextField` (or other full-width inputs) inside a `Card`:** override fixed **`344px`** width in **screen CSS** so fields stay inside the card’s padded content box (see **Tokens → `TextField` inside `Card`**). Stacked inputs: **`gap: var(--spacing-24)`** on the **`form`** column (see **Tokens → stacked `TextField` spacing**).
10. Carousels / **overflow-x** rows: confirm **inset** (spacers or scroll-padding), not flush edges.
11. Storybook / dev preview: use existing **theme** tokens in the preview.
12. **Icons:** new icon slots default to **`--icon-neutral-strong`**; use other **`--icon-*`** tokens only when the spec calls for emphasis or semantic colour (see **Tokens → Icons**).

If a requirement conflicts with this doc, **follow the user’s explicit instruction** and prefer updating this rule when the new pattern is agreed as the new standard.
